node.text:
This is a must-watch video.
And not just a quick excerpt…the entire thing, ideally on a full-sized screen with sound ON.
It’s the result of a ton of work on behalf of my friend @jessicavoruda , who is something of a sorceress when it comes to avionics installs and photography.
And it is, without question, the single most immersive representation of Oshkosh I’ve seen captured on video, truly conveying the feel and the flow of a day at @EAA Airventure.
It starts with the bustling morning energy of the air traffic controllers, tirelessly directing the inbound traffic with friendly professionalism to @WittmanAirportKOSH as the day begins.
We see crowds moving around Boeing Plaza, walking around the static aircraft displays like so many ants scurrying across the ground.
Mass arrivals at #Airventure are always amazing to see in person, but seeing them sped up in the time lapse here adds a certain choreographed energy to the process as the Piper Cubs and Mooneys arrive and park.
Then, it’s show time! 
WWII-era warbirds and modern tactical jets look amazing from any angle, but when viewed looking down from the control tower and seen cranking and banking against the background foliage, the speed and ferocity of their displays becomes evident.
After the show wraps up, the onset of dusk provides welcome relief to the searing sun as people gather in anticipation of the evening concert and the stunning night airshow.
The combination of time-lapse photography and airshow smoke creates an amazing depiction of the various aerial ballets as the white flight paths hang in place; maneuvers frozen in time against the night sky.
The night is capped off with a fireworks display that dropped every jaw in attendance last year.
I’ll be posting a story with a link to a high-resolution version of this video on Vimeo, and I strongly encourage you all to check it out.
Painful as it is to endure a summer without Airventure, this is without question the greatest taste of a day at our favorite aviation event I’ve seen, and I think it could only be enhanced if our screens could somehow produce Spotted Cow, Brats, and lifelong friends to accompany the footage.
I’ll see you there next year.

node.text:
Sad anniversary today. On this date in 2016, we lost Scotty Wilson and the incredible Bugatti 100P replica known as Le Rêve Bleu, or “Blue Dream".
The original aircraft was built in 1939 from wood and fabric, intended for air racing but never completed or flown due to the German invasion of France. 
A stunningly beautiful technological marvel, it was the source of five modern patents, including the inline engines, v-tail mixer controls, and the automatic flap system.
Today, after being rescued by various #AvGeek s at various times over the years, the original is on display in the @EAA ‘s museum in Oshkosh, Wisconsin. 
In 2009, Scotty and his friend John Lawson began constructing a replica in Oklahoma. 
Undeterred by the complete lack of blueprints or plans for the original aircraft, the duo studied it in detail to collect measurements and data for the replica.
Their efforts were generously supported by the EAA, who happily obliged their many requests for close examination and measurement of the original throughout the build process. 
Although they replaced the original #Bugatti 8-cylinder engines with two Suzuki Hayabusa engines, the remainder of the #aircraft was held to a remarkable level of accuracy.
The engines were mounted inline, and their two driveshafts drove two contrarotating propellers.
Scotty made two flights in the replica between 2015 and 2016, exploring the aircraft's handling characteristics. 
On the second flight, a brake failure resulted in a prop strike, which was subsequently repaired, and the team prepared the aircraft for one additional flight before its planned retirement to a museum.
The very last planned flight ended in tragedy when, on climbout, the left/forward engine surged to redline twice and the aircraft stalled, crashing shortly thereafter.
And while the loss of Scotty and his creation is horrible indeed, I suspect he would be happy to know to what extent his vision and talent have inspired everyone who followed and supported his endeavor. ⠀ ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

node.text:
Just a quick post today featuring what I consider to be a very questionable design decision made, in this case, by Ford on its famous Trimotor.
While it could be argued that the entire #Trimotor exemplifies questionable design decisions with its corrugated skin, external control cables, and mountains of parasite drag, some leeway is warranted; after all, the aircraft first flew in the mid 1920s.
But in these photos, we see particularly egregious design in the form of the door for the wing locker that serves as an internal wing baggage compartment.
As you can see, the floor of the baggage locker drops downward to accept cargo.
After the trunks and suitcases are loaded, the entire thing then retracts up into the wing.
It’s clever in that it holds a pretty large volume and up to 200 pounds (91 kg) of cargo without taking up any space in the wing. And because it’s contained in the wing, the weight places zero strain on the wing root.
But look at it from a pilot’s perspective, and it becomes far more ominous.
Because while that baggage locker performs its cargo hauling duty admirably, it would also perform the job of a speed brake even more so should it ever open in flight.
The #FordTrimotor isn’t known for having much excess thrust…pilots joke that the climb, cruise, and approach speeds are all 80 mph…so the thought of one of these gigantic speed brakes suddenly popping down from one wing and acting like a giant asymmetric parachute seems pretty chilling.
To be fair, I can’t provide any evidence that the system actually ever failed or created any problems. But the notion of such a failure mode existing today would be unheard of and illustrates just how far we’ve come in aircraft design and engineering.

node.text:
Earlier this morning, my friend Justin who runs the @pilottopilot podcast posted a photo showing a very interesting Grumman TBM Avenger.
Avengers are interesting to begin with, of course. First flown in 1941, nearly ten thousand were built, and served as torpedo bombers during WWII.
They were manufactured by two different companies, and the last letter of the designation indicates which; the TBF was built by Grumman, and the TBM by General Motors.
They served well in their torpedo bombing role, and when retirement loomed, some made an amusing transition. 
With enemy submarines littering the ocean floor and generally making less of a nuisance of themselves, the TBM fleet was left with nothing to bomb…until the aerial firefighting industry took notice. 
With wildfires raging in North America, these companies procured surplus TBMs and transformed them from a role that delivers death and destruction into one that prevents those things from occurring.
A number of water bombers (eventually 43 examples) began serving in their new role in 1958 and a portion went on to fulfill that role until 2012…roughly twice the amount of time in their civilian role as in the military.
Despite this admirable service, nearly all of the 78 Avengers that exist today wear military colors, and as far as I know, only one or maybe two are adorned in their civilian firefighting paint schemes.
With so many surviving airframes, I think it’s a shame so few reflect this important role in history, and this is reflected in other types, as well; virtually no recognition is given to the post-WWII aerial firefighting industry of the 1950s-1970s.
And if you ask me, it’s a shame.
But if, like me, you like to bask in this colorful part of aviation history, there’s a solution in the form of a dedicated Instagram account.
It’s called @civilized_warbirds and features military aircraft painted and serving in civilian roles, and the content is just fantastic.

When it comes to front-row footage of #Airventure, few people have better seats than @dutchninja79 .
He grew up helping to direct and marshal aircraft into and out of the event, and over the decades, he’s refined the process to resemble a gigantic, ever-moving symphony of airplanes into and out of the airport.
Here, at #OSH21 last week, he captured some very interesting footage of a @dutchninja79 Boeing C-17 Globemaster III advancing the thrust levers for takeoff.
It’s not at all uncommon to see the C-17’s engines create small tornados that extend from the intake to the ground…but I for one have never seen any of those tendrils reach around from one engine intake to another.
I hate to post things without a good explanation of what you’re seeing, so I made an effort to learn more about this phenomenon by reaching out to not one but two current C-17 pilots…and neither had ever seen it, nor did they know how to explain it.
What we do know is that the flow in and around the engine intakes, particularly at higher thrust settings, is incredibly complex.
The resulting vortices aren’t always visible, but in the right blend of temperature and humidity, the fluid dynamics come to life and put on a great show.

This has been the second #Airventure at which I’ve had the privilege of introducing others to the event for their first time, and I’ve come to realize that such introductions are perhaps as memorable as the event itself. 
In 2019, my friends @stratojet47 and @brazenfly drove over from Michigan and camped with me and my Mooney owner friend @theflyingohiofox .
They happened to arrive at the campsite just as the sun was approaching the horizon and as the Cessna mass arrival was taking place. 
The combination of golden summer evening light and eighty-six airplanes trundling past on their way to their respective campsites was surreal, and it served as a perfect introduction to #OSH19.
This year, my friend @aligero.us and his dad made the drive up from Ohio; it was their first time visiting and in addition to enjoying the show, they got to spend some memorable father/son time taking it all in. 
Seeing the event through the eyes of first-timers is both entertaining and rewarding - to those of us who have been attending for years, it reminds us just how impressive the event truly is, and how good friends are the glue that holds all the aviation together. 

#OSH21

My goodness, what an amazing 170!
This one parked next to me yesterday and is a veritable catalog of the most desirable modifications. 
210 horsepower drives a beautiful carbon fiber propeller, making even the tallest departure end obstacles disappear into insignificance during climbout. 
@cessna 180 gear legs are adorned with awesome 29”@akbushwheels that soak up the harshest runway surfaces and coddle the airframe in plush comfort. 
The panel is fully Garminized®, with just about every sweet @garminaviation addition one could reasonably want. 
The interior is modern and technical, stripped down for weight savings while improved with nice leather upholstery. 
And the exterior blends brightly polished aluminum with retro yet unique paint, making it really pop when parked next to more traditional examples. 
Man, what a magnificent beast.

EDIT: The storm is gone and all is well!

An old friend of mine who has flown everything from Beavers to A330s once opined, “Wings don't fall off airplanes. Airplanes fall off their wings. It is, after all, the wing that does the flying.”
Tonight’s goal? Prevent my wing from flying.
It’s day three here at @EAA #Airventure #OSH21, and tonight’s forecast is grim:
 • • •
TEMPO 2904/2906 33035G50KT 3/4SM +TSRA BKN012CB
• • •
In plain English, this means that from now until about 1am, winds are forecast to occasionally gust as high as 57 miles per hour. 
The flaps-up, power-off stall speed of my airplane is about 58 miles per hour at maximum takeoff weight. 
This means that if the wind gusts as strongly as forecast, Scruffy...in his current, unloaded state...just might make an attempt to go flying all by himself. 
Hopefully, my tie downs will prevent any such unauthorized jaunts from taking place...but I’ve got a backup plan to further assist.
In an effort to prevent Scruffy’s wing from generating enough lift to take flight, I copied my friend @js170b and installed some spoilers that I purchased from Wal-Mart.
Spoilers in the form of foam pool noodles.
While normally utilized as fun floatation devices for beachgoers, they do an admirable job of disrupting airflow over the top surface of a wing when taped to it. 
The finely engineered @Cessna airfoil, normally able to deftly lift 2,200 pounds aloft effectively becomes about as aerodynamically efficient as the wings people glue to the trunk lids of their 1992 Honda Civic Sedans...which is to say, not at all.
For now, the distant rumble of thunder is punctuated by the staccato reports of tie down stakes being securely hammered into pace as airplane owners batten down the hatches, hoping for the best but preparing for the worst. 
Wish us luck, AvGeeks, and we’ll see you on the other side.

I always knew the Howard DGA was a luxurious airplane, but it takes on a whole new level when you pop your head inside. 
Although pressed into military service during WWII in roles such as a utility and medical transport, the type soon evolved back into its original intended role as a luxurious personal transport. 
It was essentially the private jet of its time, a favorite of wealthy individuals and corporations alike. 
Yesterday, a good friend introduced me to the owner of this exquisite example here at #OSH21 , and it was fun to learn a bit about the type from him.
The side window rolls up and down like a vintage automobile, and the control harmony and handling are apparently both exceptional, and make it a very honest, straightforward airplane to fly.

node.text:
It’s the first day of #OSH21, and the sunny morning is punctuated by the snarl of T-6s taking off in formation and P-51s whistling by in their overhead breaks. 
Soon, the Ford Trimotor and Bell 47 will add to the wonderful din as they swarm about the airspace, taking people for ride after ride throughout the day. 
Later, more military jets will arrive, their afterburners interrupting conversations in the most glorious manner possible. 
Oshkosh has smells, too. 
Coffee and bacon join forces to finish waking you up in the morning.
The scent of vintage aircraft interiors greets you when you pop your head into a cockpit to admire them; a mesmerizing blend of leather, engine oil, and decades worth of adventuring. 
And on the other end of history, turbine powered aircraft announce their arrival with the aroma of kerosene as the jet exhaust wafts over the surrounding admirers. 
Collectively, there might not be a more sublime way to start your day, and especially after last year, we savor each moment and file it away in our memories to help get us through the winter ahead. 
Welcome to #OSH21 , day one!

node.text:
The brand new Cessna SkyCourier is here at #OSH21!
What an awesome opportunity to see a new, clean-sheet Cessna unveiled to the world!
I’ll do my best to learn more about it for you wonderful people, but for now, check out the asymmetric exhaust pipes!
They precisely divert exhaust gasses into the spiraling propeller slipstream in such a manner as to avoid subjecting the leading edge to dangerously hot temperatures. 
I have to go get a burrito now, so enjoy these initial shots and join me in congratulating @cessna and @textronaviation  on this awesome accomplishment!

node.text:
Sad to hear of the passing of Dale Snodgrass.
I’m fortunate to have spent just a bit of time with the man. 
The year was 1999. I was at Oshkosh, enjoying the show with a friend of mine, @melissa_courtney1 .
At the time, Melissa worked for @pattyaerobatics as a part of the ground crew. She invited me to stop by that group's tent in the North 40 for a burger and brat.
As I sat down to enjoy my food, a guy sat next to me to do the same, and struck up conversation. He asked me what I was flying and what ratings I was working on.
I explained that I'd mostly been flying the Cessna 172R, but had just started flying the Mooney M20R Ovation...which was, I explained, quite a bit faster and more challenging to fly well than the Cessna.
He became very interested, asking about my training progression, what was so different about the Mooney, etc.
Clearly, I thought, this guy has the bug and must be interested in learning to fly!
So I went on and on, explaining how slippery the Mooney was, how it had speed brakes, and how descents had to be planned very carefully if one wanted to set him/herself up properly for a good approach.
He continued to listen intently and asked insightful questions about my work toward my instrument and commercial before politely excusing himself and leaving.
It was then that Melissa came over and said "You know who that was, right?"
"Sure", I said, "I didn't get his name, but he's totally got the flying bug and it sounds like he might start taking flying lessons. I'm super excited for him!"
"Uh, yeah...that was Dale Snodgrass", she replied.
“Wait - you mean the guy who was flying the Tomcat in that famous carrier low pass photo?"
"Yep", she said. "You were just talking with the guy who has more Tomcat time than anyone on the planet, and who used to command the US Navy fighter wing of the Atlantic Fleet."
So that’s how I met Dale. By blathering on about what a hot ride the Mooney is and emphasizing how much more demanding it is to fly compared to a 172.
It is said that when we pass away, we do so twice; first physically, and then, after our name is spoken for the last time. 
It’s safe to say that in the 2nd case, Dale will live on forever.
